To implement a cache in JavaScript that allows garbage collection of unused entries, you can use `WeakMap` and `WeakRef` together.

### Key points:
- **`WeakMap`** holds keys weakly, so if there are no other references to the key object, the entry can be garbage collected.
- **`WeakRef`** holds a weak reference to a value, allowing the value to be garbage collected if there are no strong references elsewhere.
- Using both, you can cache values associated with object keys without preventing garbage collection of keys or values.

---

### Example: Cache with `WeakMap` and `WeakRef`

```js
class Cache {
  constructor() {
    // WeakMap keys are objects; values are WeakRefs to cached values
    this._cache = new WeakMap();
  }

  set(key, value) {
    // Store a weak reference to the value
    this._cache.set(key, new WeakRef(value));
  }

  get(key) {
    const ref = this._cache.get(key);
    if (!ref) return undefined; // no entry

    const value = ref.deref();
    if (value === undefined) {
      // Value was garbage collected, remove the entry
      this._cache.delete(key);
    }
    return value;
  }

  has(key) {
    const ref = this._cache.get(key);
    if (!ref) return false;

    if (ref.deref() === undefined) {
      this._cache.delete(key);
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  }
}
```

### Usage:

```js
const cache = new Cache();

let objKey = { id: 1 };
let value = { data: "some heavy data" };

cache.set(objKey, value);

console.log(cache.get(objKey)); // { data: "some heavy data" }

value = null; // Remove strong reference to value

// At some point later, if GC runs, value may be collected
console.log(cache.get(objKey)); // May be undefined if GC collected the value

objKey = null; // Remove strong reference to key

// Now the WeakMap entry can be collected as well
```

---

### Explanation:
- The `WeakMap` holds keys weakly, so if `objKey` is no longer referenced elsewhere, the entry is removed automatically.
- The `WeakRef` holds a weak reference to the value, so if the value is no longer referenced strongly elsewhere, it can be garbage collected.
- The `get` method uses `deref()` to get the value if it still exists, otherwise cleans up the cache entry.

---

### Notes:
- Garbage collection timing is non-deterministic.
- `WeakRef` and `FinalizationRegistry` are relatively new and may not be supported in all environments.
- This pattern is useful when you want to cache data without preventing GC of keys or values.

---

References:
- [MDN WeakMap](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/WeakMap)
- [MDN WeakRef](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/WeakRef)

